ite its population being predominately Muslim. He shows how such actions have given Senegal an inflated political and economic position and status as a highly credit-worthy nation even as its domestic economy has faltered. Exploring these and many other aspects of Senegal’s political economy and its interface with the international community, Ralph demonstrates that the international reputation of any nation—not just Senegal—is based on deep structural biases.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCapitalxSocial aspectszSenegal. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aafrica, african, senegal, democracy, democracies, academic, scholarly, educational, college, university, higher education, research, nations, continent, international, global, globalization, diplomatic, diplomacy, politics, political, poli sci, politician, postcolonial, colonial, development, era, time period, history, historical, influential, muslim, religion, faith, belief, socialist, economic, economy, money, wealth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226198606423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226198606/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles